{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508941"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:10:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:10:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11363"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11363"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.01,0.02,0.26,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4008"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100266"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4008"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11363"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82664"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1227"},{"type":"tags","id":"2967"},{"type":"tags","id":"4340"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4968"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5231"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7377"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8072"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27002"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30948"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34076"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42580"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43216"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100266"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA healthy 24-year-old woman, G2P0 at 17+2 weeks presents for a routine antenatal review. The midwife has performed a routine urine dipstick which is negative for ketones and leukocytes and positive for glucose +. Her medical history is unremarkable and a point of care blood sugar was normal. She denies feeling increasingly thirsty or consuming more fluids, nor does she experience any pain on urination. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn physical examination, her blood pressure is 118/78 mmHg, pulse 82/min and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. Her BMI is 23. There is no reduced skin turgor and her capillary refill is less than two seconds.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the urine dipstick finding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Normal finding","Type 1 diabetes mellitus","Type 2 diabetes mellitus","Gestational diabetes mellitus","Alimentary glycosuria"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal finding - \u003C/strong\u003EGlycosuria in pregnancy is a normal phenomenon due to increased renal blood flow and glomerular filtration that exceeds the resorption capacity of the tubules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGestational diabetes mellitus (GDM)\u003C/strong\u003E \u2013 Urine dipstick is not a diagnostic investigation for GDM. Screening for GDM is traditionally performed by the oral glucose tolerance test (OGTT) or combined testing of fasting blood glucose and HbA1c (5.9% or above). She does not have any risk factors that would justify and early OGTT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 1 diabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EType 2 diabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E are unlikely given that the patient denies other symptoms (polyphagia and polydipsia) and the urine dipstick is negative for ketones. Additionally, her physical examination suggests that dehydration is not present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlimentary glycosuria \u003C/strong\u003Erefers to a transient increase in renal glucose excretion following high quantity consumption of carbohydrates. Although this is possible explanation for the patient\u0027s presentation, it is less likely than the \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal finding \u003C/strong\u003Eof glycosuria in pregnancy which is thought to be found in up to 50% of pregnant women at \u003Cstrong\u003Esome point\u003C/strong\u003E during the pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Asymptomatic glycosuria in pregnant women is a normal finding","Diagnosis of gestational diabetes mellitus is made using an oral glucose tolerance test rather than urine dipstick"],"references":["Alto WA. No need for glycosuria/proteinuria screen in pregnant women. J Fam Pract. 2005 Nov;54(11):978-83. PMID: 16266604. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16266604/","Coolen JC, Verhaeghe J. Physiology and clinical value of glycosuria after a glucose challenge during pregnancy. Eur J Obstet Gynecol Reprod Biol. 2010 Jun;150(2):132-6. doi: 10.1016/j.ejogrb.2010.02.032. Epub 2010 Mar 5. PMID: 20207065. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20207065/","Agbozo F, Abubakari A, Narh C, Jahn A. Accuracy of glycosuria, random blood glucose and risk factors as selective screening tools for gestational diabetes mellitus in comparison with universal diagnosing. BMJ Open Diabetes Res Care. 2018 Jun 15;6(1):e000493. doi: 10.1136/bmjdrc-2017-000493. PMID: 29942522; PMCID: PMC6014183. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6014183/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82664"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11363"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82664"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-25T09:18:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-25